Mitotic chromosomes form through long, overlapping and self-repelling DNA loops, generated by the Condensin complexes!

Check out our newest paper here, and see below for a short Bluetorial!
www.cell.com/cell/fulltex...
Kai and I used the recently established LoopTrace technology to trace the structure of single mitotic chromosomes in human cells in a very mild & structure pre-serving manner.
Analyzing these traces, we found evidence for continuously growing loops, and our degron-based experiments showed that these loops are built by the Condensin complexes.
We found that Condensins are also responsible for the backfolding of DNA at much larger genomic distances: up to 6-8 megabases.

Using a dynamic polymer constrained only by available quantitative Condensin chromatin-binding data, we could recapitulate the formation of native mitotic chromosome rods!

Two features were essential for that ->

Feature 1: Condensins pass each other. This leads to the formation of large, extensively overlapping loops with sizes up to 6-8 Mb.

Feature 2: DNA self-repulsion. This leads to self-organization and stacking of loops into the rod-shape.

Our model perfectly recapitulated our tracing data & the Condensin localization pattern as quantified recently in Walther et al. 2018. 
rupress.org/jcb/article/...
We thus propose that mitotic chromosome shape is dictated by Condensin-driven extrusion of long and overlapping loops up to a density set by chromatin self-repulsion.

This has been an excellent collaboration together with Kai Beckwith in the @ellenberglab.bsky.social @embl.org. Thanks a lot to Kai, Jan, Natalia, and our collaborator Ralf Jungmann!!

A summary of the work can also be read at the @embl.org press release:
www.embl.org/news/science...

We're less than a week away from our first service. We're looking forward to welcoming you Sunday 30th March at 6pm (for dinner) or 7.30 (for the service) at St Mary & St John, Cowley Road.

Here's what you can expect:
We will begin at 6pm with a shared dinner of curry and rice prepared by Oxford Community Kitchen. All food will be vegetarian, with a vegan and gluten free option.
The meal will open with a welcome and grace from Martha, the Vicar of St Mary and St John Cowley, after which we will eat and get to know one another.
At 7pm we will begin to clear up the food and tables, anyone who is able is welcome to help with this. You can also continue your conversations with other guests, or take a few minutes to yourself.
At 7.15 we will begin to play some quiet music as we transition towards the reflective space, anyone who does not want to stay for the service is welcome to make their way out at this point.
At 7.30 we begin the service of which will take us through a cycle of prayer, readings or reflection, space for contemplation and music.
There are a variety of options for seating, including chairs and beanbags, and we welcome you to bring crafts or fidget toys if you would like (We‚Äôll be bringing our knitting and our sketch books!)
The service will end at 8.15 by sharing the following grace: "The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ. And the love of God. And the fellowship of the Holy Spirit. Be with us all evermore."

- Discord Listening Party on Thursday, March 27th 2025 at 7PM Central Daylight Time
- Vinyl Preorders soon

(Un)fortunately there‚Äôs not much you can do about it. Can you reasonably report a loud motorcycle driving by you if you cant see the license plate and it drives by quickly enough to be gone within a few seconds?
Yet you can probably hear it‚Äôs rumbling for a minute or two before it passes by you and again after.
Toronto‚Äôs noise bylaw limits the noise to 92 dBA from the exhaust at idle, and 96 dBA otherwise, measured at 50cm from the exhaust
This relates to about 70dBA if you were 10m away at a sidewalk or 64 dBA at your house 20m away. These levels seem on the face of it, reasonable. But there are a few problems with this.

Much of vehicular noise is at the lower frequencies so applying an A-weighting to it (the A in dBA) discounts the effect of the low frequencies. This may be accounted for in the limit. (I don‚Äôt know)
Usually there are adjustments made to annoying noise qualities like tonality, annoyance and time of day. These aren‚Äôt noted in the limits.

For example if the noise has a tonality to it, we add 5dB. So a 65 dBA measured noise level ‚Äúfeels‚Äù like 70 dBA because it‚Äôs more annoying. Or when you‚Äôre at home relaxing doing quiet things after work, and the motorcycle drives by, it‚Äôs more annoying
Another issue is that the windows and walls of your home, block more high frequency sound than low freq. so it sounds even louder/more annoying inside your home than other sounds.
